                Intimacies.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia anchor_text="principes illi Diodotus, Philo, Antiochus, Posidonius" hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Cic[eronis] Magistri
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Cicero"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                The teachers of Cicero.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia anchor_text="omnia praecepta philosophiae referu[n]tur ad vita[m]" hand="English_secretary">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Omnia pra[e]cepta philosophia[e] referuntur ad vitam
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                All precepts of philosophy concern life.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Cur Cic[ero] philosophia[m] latinis literis ia[m] illustrabat, tam sero
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Cicero"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Why Cicero illuminates philosophy with Latin letters already, so late. <!-- FSF: not sure about iam and tam sero -->
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia anchor_text="Graecis institutionibus eruditi, ea qui didicerant, cum ciuibus suis communicare non potera[n]t" hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Gra[e]cis institutionibus eruditi, artes ciuibus co[mmun]icare no[n] poterant
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Those taught by Greek instructions cannot communicate the arts to the citizens.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Philosophia leuatio a[nim]i a[e]groti est
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Relief of the sick mind is philosophy. 
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Qua[e] optima via est, ad philosop. cognitione[m]
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                The best way is that to recognition of philosophy. 
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia anchor_text="seriésque rerum" hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Reru[m] series
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                A series of things.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia anchor_text="authoritatis in disputando quàm rationis" hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Authoritas. Ratio
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Authority, reasoning.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EL">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        αὐτὸς ἔφη
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                He himself said so. <!-- the traditional ratification of Pythagorean dicta -->
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Iam respondet tertio loco illi rei qua[m] supra sibi tertia[m] proposint
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                <!-- FSF: not sure about this -->
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia anchor_text="no[n] enim hominum interitu sente[n]tiae quoque occidunt" hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        No[n] ho[m]i[nu]m interitu se[n]tentia[e] quoq[ue] occidunt.
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                'When men die, their doctrines do not perish with them' [LCL 268:12-13].
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia anchor_text="singulas disciplinas percipere magnum est" hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Singulas disciplinas percipere magnum est
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                It is powerful to understand the single systems. 
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        tame[n] qui veri volu[n]t esse academici o[mn]es tenere debe[n]t
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Nonetheless, those who want to be academics must comprehend everything.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia anchor_text="indociles quidam tardíque sunt, admonendi videntur saepius" hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Indociles sa[e]pius, admonendi
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Ignorant is more often, admonishing. <!-- FSF: nor sure how to translate this -->
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Magna similitudo inter vera &amp; falsa
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Grat likeness among the true and false.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia anchor_text="procas Academia" hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Academia Procax
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Undisciplined academy.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="English_secretary">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        nihil est q[uod] expedire ta[m] facile possimus
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                There is nothing that we can disengage so easily.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia anchor_text="vsque ad nostram viguit aetatem" hand="English_secretary">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        illa r[ati]o &amp; vsq[ue] ad n[ost]ram viguit a[e]tate[m].
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                This method acquired strength even until our age.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="English_secretary">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        gra[e]cis institutionibus eruditi
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Taught by Greek instructions.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
